1.2 Why was it built?
Before 2014, developers used Objective-C to build Apple apps using the Cocoa and Cocoa Touch frameworks. Objective-C was powerful but had a complicated syntax. Swift was designed to be cleaner and safer while maintaining full compatibility with the older Objective-C codebases.
Here is a direct comparison of how you display “Hello, World!” on a screen in three different languages.
How it looked in Objective-C (before 2014):
#import &lt;UIKit/UIKit.h&gt;

@interface ViewController : UIViewController
@end

@implementation ViewController

- (void)viewDidLoad {
    [super viewDidLoad];

    UILabel *label = [[UILabel alloc] init];
    label.text = @"Hello, World!";
    [label sizeToFit];
    label.center = self.view.center;

    [self.view addSubview:label];
}

@end
How it looks now in Swift (specifically using SwiftUI):
import SwiftUI

struct ContentView: View {
    var body: some View {
        Text("Hello, World!")
    }
}
How that same concept looks in React (JavaScript):
import React from 'react';

export default function App() {
  return (
    &lt;div style={{ display: 'flex', justifyContent: 'center', alignItems: 'center', height: '100vh' }}&gt;
      &lt;h1&gt;Hello, World!&lt;/h1&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
  );
}

2.2 The Root Entry Point
When a user taps an app icon on their iPhone, iOS looks for the @main attribute to know strictly where the app officially starts executing.
Here is the Swift Entry Point (App.swift):
import SwiftUI

@main
struct MyApp: App {
    var body: some Scene {
        WindowGroup {
            ContentView() // ⬅️ Points to the first Screen
        }
    }
}






NoteReact Equivalent (index.js)





import React from 'react';
import ReactDOM from 'react-dom/client';
import App from './App';

const root = ReactDOM.createRoot(document.getElementById('root'));
root.render(
  &lt;React.StrictMode&gt;
    &lt;App /&gt; {/* ⬅️ Points to the first Screen */}
  &lt;/React.StrictMode&gt;
);

2.3 How Screens Work (Views)
In Swift, there is no generic &lt;div&gt;. A screen is always built strictly as a Struct conforming to the View protocol.
Here is what ContentView.swift looks like. Keep an eye out for exactly how the answers to your common architectural questions map directly onto the code structure:
import SwiftUI

struct ContentView: View {
    // ⬇️ Q3: Where is the data? 
    // Data is held explicitly inside the struct instance using Property Wrappers like @State.
    @State private var userName: String = "Charlotte" 

    // ⬇️ Q2: When does render happen? 
    // ANY time the property marked as @State explicitly changes, the 'body' automatically re-renders.
    var body: some View {
        VStack {
            Text("Hello, \(userName)")

            Button("Change Name") {
                // ⬇️ Q1: Is this single-threaded?
                // Yes. By default, ALL UI code executes strictly on the Main Thread.
                userName = "Swift Developer"
            }
        }
    }
}

1. Semicolons are Dead
Fact: Swift does not require semicolons ; at the end of statements.

In modern JavaScript, semicolons are technically optional but are widely enforced by linters (like Prettier/ESLint) to prevent interpreter errors.
In Swift, semicolons are genuinely discouraged by the compiler.
Rule: Only use a semicolon if you are writing two completely separate statements on the exact same line (which you should rarely ever do).

// Correct Swift
let name = "Charlotte"
let age = 28

// Discouraged Swift (Do not do this)
let name = "Charlotte"; let age = 28;


2. Variables and Constants (let vs var)
Fact: let in Swift is functionally identical to const in JavaScript. var in Swift is identical to let in JavaScript.

Rule: Always default to using let when declaring new data. Only change it to var if the Swift compiler explicitly throws an error telling you that the value needs to mutate later.







NoteWhat does this look like in JavaScript?





// JavaScript
const name = "Charlotte" // Immutable
let age = 28 // Mutable



Swift Equivalent:
// Swift
let name = "Charlotte" // Immutable (Use this default)
var age = 28 // Mutable (Use only if changing)


3. Writing Functions
Fact: Swift functions use the func keyword, enforce strict types on both the arguments and the output, and explicitly mandate how you call them.
Key differences compared to JavaScript:

Arguments require explicit types (e.g., name: String).
A function’s return type is declared with a right-facing arrow -&gt;.
When invoking a function, you must explicitly write out the parameter’s name to make the code highly legible.







NoteWhat does this look like in JavaScript & React?





// 1. Standard JavaScript Function
function greet(name) {
    return "Hello " + name;
}

greet("Charlotte"); // Called without explicitly naming the parameters


// 2. React Functional Component (Returns UI)
export default function Greet({ name }) {
    return &lt;h1&gt;Hello {name}&lt;/h1&gt;;
}

// Called using JSX, where props act similarly to named parameters
&lt;Greet name="Charlotte" /&gt;



Swift Equivalent:
// 1. Standard Swift Function
func greet(name: String) -&gt; String {
    return "Hello \(name)" // Notice string interpolation uses \( ) not ${ }
}

let message = greet(name: "Charlotte") // ⬅️ MUST explicitly write 'name:' 


// 2. SwiftUI View (Struct returning UI)
struct Greet: View {
    let name: String

    var body: some View {
        Text("Hello \(name)")
    }
}

// ⬇️ Called exactly like a function using named parameters!
Greet(name: "Charlotte")
Function Parameter Omitting: If you want Swift to behave exactly like JavaScript and let you omit the parameter name when calling a function, you explicitly place an underscore _ before the parameter name in the definition.
func fastGreet(_ name: String) -&gt; String {
    return "Hey \(name)"
}

// Now it looks exactly like JavaScript when invoked:
let fastMessage = fastGreet("Charlotte")


4. String Interpolation
Fact: Swift uses \() to inject variables into strings. - In JavaScript, you switch to backticks and use ${variable}. - In Swift, you keep standard double quotes "" and inject the variable natively using a backslash and parentheses \(variable).


5. Parentheses in Control Flow
Fact: Swift deliberately drops the parentheses () around if, guard, and switch statements. - Rule: The curly braces {} encompassing the block are strictly mandatory, but the parentheses holding the boolean condition are entirely omitted to reduce visual noise.






NoteWhat does this look like in JavaScript?





if (age &gt; 18) {
    console.log("Adult");
}



Swift Equivalent:
// ⬇️ No parenthesis needed around 'age &gt; 18'
if age &gt; 18 { 
    print("Adult")
}


6. Multi-Line Dot Syntax (Modifier Chaining)
Fact: Swift heavily relies on chaining methods together using dot . notation. For readability in enterprise applications, these chains are almost always broken across multiple vertical lines. - Rule: The dot . must start on the new line, typically aligned directly beneath the object it modifies.






NoteWhat does this look like in JavaScript & React?





// JavaScript Method Chaining (Data Handling)
const activeUsers = users
    .filter(user =&gt; user.isActive)
    .sort((a, b) =&gt; a.id - b.id);

// React UI Equivalent (Applying styles/actions)
// React rarely uses dot-chaining for components; instead, you stack physical props or merge class strings:
&lt;button 
    className="bg-blue-500 text-white font-bold py-2 px-4 rounded"
    onClick={handleTap}
&gt;
    Enter Dashboard
&lt;/button&gt;



Swift Equivalent (SwiftUI Modifiers): In SwiftUI, you strictly apply styles and behaviors using “View Modifiers”, which are just functions chained vertically via dot notation.
// Enterprise App Snippet: Structuring a styled button
Button(action: handleTap) {
    Text("Enter Dashboard")
}
.font(.headline)
.fontWeight(.bold)
.foregroundColor(.white)
.padding(.vertical, 12)
.padding(.horizontal, 24)
.background(Color.blue)
.cornerRadius(8)

1. VStack (Vertical Stack)






NoteWhat does this look like in React?





// React equivalent using inline Flexbox styles
&lt;div style={{ display: 'flex', flexDirection: 'column', alignItems: 'center', gap: '8px' }}&gt;
    &lt;h1&gt;Top Item&lt;/h1&gt;
    &lt;p&gt;Bottom Item&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;



Swift Equivalent:
// Swift automatically stacks vertically and injects a default Apple-standard gap
VStack {
    Text("Top Item")
        .font(.title)
    Text("Bottom Item")
}


2. HStack (Horizontal Stack)






NoteWhat does this look like in React?





// React equivalent using inline Flexbox styles
&lt;div style={{ display: 'flex', flexDirection: 'row', alignItems: 'center', gap: '8px' }}&gt;
    &lt;span&gt;Left Item&lt;/span&gt;
    &lt;span&gt;Right Item&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;



Swift Equivalent:
// Swift automatically links them horizontally
HStack {
    Text("Left Item")
    Text("Right Item")
}


3. ZStack (Depth Stack)
Fact: ZStack physically stacks visual elements on top of each other strictly along the Z-axis (depth). - Rule: The first item written systematically in the code is placed at the mathematical bottom, and subsequent items visually stack sequentially on top of it.






NoteWhat does this look like in React?





// React typically overrides standard flow using relative and absolute positioning
&lt;div style={{ position: 'relative', width: '200px', height: '200px' }}&gt;
    &lt;img src="background.jpg" style={{ position: 'absolute', width: '100%', zIndex: 0 }} /&gt;
    &lt;h1 style={{ position: 'absolute', zIndex: 10 }}&gt;Text on top&lt;/h1&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;



Swift Equivalent:
// No manual CSS absolute positioning required
ZStack {
    Image("background") // Bottom physical layer
        .resizable()

    Text("Text on top") // Top physical layer
        .foregroundColor(.white)
}

4.2 Making Grids
Fact: In React, creating a responsive grid requires verbose CSS Grid definitions (grid-template-columns, gap, fr fractions). In Swift, wrappers like LazyVGrid naturally handle the complex fractional mathematics cleanly at compile-time.
Why are they called Lazy? - Because they only evaluate identically when elements physically overlap the viewable screen. If you inject 10,000 items in a grid manually, Swift only physically renders the 10 that the user is currently looking at, guaranteeing flawless performance automatically.






NoteWhat does this look like in React?





// React using bulky CSS Grid
&lt;div style={{ 
    display: 'grid', 
    gridTemplateColumns: 'repeat(2, 1fr)', 
    gap: '16px' 
}}&gt;
    &lt;div&gt;Item 1&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div&gt;Item 2&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div&gt;Item 3&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div&gt;Item 4&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;



Swift Equivalent:
// ⬇️ 1. Define the grid spacing mathematically (Two identically flexible columns)
let columns = [
    GridItem(.flexible()),
    GridItem(.flexible())
]

var body: some View {
    // ⬇️ 2. Apply it cleanly to the Lazy wrapper
    LazyVGrid(columns: columns, spacing: 16) {
        Text("Item 1")
        Text("Item 2")
        Text("Item 3")
        Text("Item 4")
    }
}
Fact vs Verbosity Conclusion: Notice exactly how much less verbose the SwiftUI wrapper visually acts. You explicitly define the mechanical structure of your layouts once as pure data (let columns), and inject them into the standard logical Grid components—entirely avoiding manual CSS string-map configuration.

